==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Foul
<hw>Foul</hw> <pr>(foul)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Fowl</er>.]</ety> <def>A bird.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foul</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Foul
<hw>Foul</hw> <pr>(foul)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
Fouler <pr>(-⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Foulest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>foul</ets>,
<ets>ful</ets>, AS. <ets>f⟦umac⟧l</ets>; akin to D. <ets>vuil</ets>, G.
<ets>faul</ets> rotten, OHG. <ets>f⟦umac⟧l</ets>, Icel.
<ets>f⟦umac⟧l</ets> foul, fetid; Dan. <ets>fuul</ets>, Sw.
<ets>ful</ets> foul, Goth. <ets>f⟦umac⟧ls</ets> fetid, Lith.
<ets>puti</ets> to be putrid, L. <ets>putere</ets> to stink, be putrid,
<ets>pus</ets> pus, Gr. <grk>py`on</grk> pus, to cause to rot, Skr.
<ets>p⟦umac⟧y</ets> to stink. ⟦root⟧82. Cf. <er>Defile</er> to foul,
<er>File</er> to foul, <er>Filth</er>, <er>Pus</er>,
<er>Putrid</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Covered with, or containing,
extraneous matter which is injurious, noxious, offensive, or
obstructive; filthy; dirty; not clean; polluted; nasty; defiled; <as>as,
a <ex>foul</ex> cloth; <ex>foul</ex> hands; a <ex>foul</ex> chimney;
<ex>foul</ex> air; a ship's bottom is <ex>foul</ex> when overgrown with
barnacles; a gun becomes <ex>foul</ex> from repeated firing; a well is
<ex>foul</ex> with polluted water.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My face is <qex>foul</qex> with weeping.</q> <rj><qau>Job. xvi.
16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Scurrilous; obscene or profane; abusive; <as>as,
<ex>foul</ex> words; <ex>foul</ex> language.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hateful; detestable; shameful; odious;
wretched.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>foul</xex> with Sycorax.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who first seduced them to that <qex>foul</qex> revolt?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Loathsome; disgusting; <as>as, a <ex>foul</ex>
disease</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Ugly; homely; poor.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us, like merchants, show our <qex>foulest</qex> wares.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Not favorable; unpropitious; not fair or
advantageous; <as>as, a <ex>foul</ex> wind; a <ex>foul</ex> road</as>;
cloudy or rainy; stormy; not fair; -- said of the weather, sky,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So <qex>foul</qex> a sky clears not without a storm.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Not conformed to the established rules and customs
of a game, conflict, test, etc.; unfair; dishonest; dishonorable;
cheating; <as>as, <ex>foul</ex> play</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Having freedom of motion interfered with by
collision or entanglement; entangled; -- opposed to <ant>clear</ant>;
<as>as, a rope or cable may get <ex>foul</ex> while paying it
out</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 590 --></p>

<p><cs><col><b>Foul anchor</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Anchor</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Foul ball</b></col>
<fld>(Baseball)</fld>, <cd>a ball that first strikes the ground outside
of the foul ball lines, or rolls outside of certain limits.</cd> --
<col><b>Foul ball lines</b></col> <fld>(Baseball)</fld>, <cd>lines from
the home base, through the first and third bases, to the boundary of the
field.</cd> -- <col><b>Foul berth</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a
berth in which a ship is in danger of fouling another vesel.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Foul bill</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Foul bill of
health</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a certificate, duly authenticated, that a
ship has come from a place where a contagious disorder prevails, or that
some of the crew are infected.</cd> -- <col><b>Foul copy</b></col>,
<cd>a rough draught, with erasures and corrections; -- opposed to
<xex>fair</xex> or <xex>clean copy</xex>.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Some writers boast
of negligence, and others would be ashamed to show their <xex>foul
copies</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Cowper.</au> -- <col><b>Foul proof</b></col>,
<cd>an uncorrected proof; a proof containing an excessive quantity of
errors.</cd> -- <col><b>Foul strike</b></col> <fld>(Baseball)</fld>,
<cd>a strike by the batsman when any part of his person is outside of
the lines of his position.</cd> -- <col><b>To fall foul</b></col>,
<cd>to fall out; to quarrel.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧If they be
any ways offended, they <xex>fall foul</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Burton.</au> --
<mcol><col><b>To fall foul of</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To run foul
of</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See under <er>Fall</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To
make foul water</b></col>, <cd>to sail in such shallow water that the
ship's keel stirs the mud at the bottom.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foul</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Foul
<hw>Foul</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Fouled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fouling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make filthy; to
defile; to daub; to dirty; to soil; <as>as, to <ex>foul</ex> the face or
hands with mire</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>To incrust (the bore of a gun)
with burnt powder in the process of firing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cover (a ship's bottom) with anything that
impered its sailing; <as>as, a bottom <ex>fouled</ex> with
barnacles</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To entangle, so as to impede motion; <as>as, to
<ex>foul</ex> a rope or cable in paying it out</as>; to come into
collision with; <as>as, one boat <ex>fouled</ex> the other in a
race</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foul</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Foul
<hw>Foul</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become clogged with
burnt powder in the process of firing, as a gun.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To become entagled, as ropes; to come into collision
with something; <as>as, the two boats <ex>fouled</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foul</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Foul
<hw>Foul</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An entanglement; a
collision, as in a boat race.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Baseball)</fld> <def>See <cref>Foul ball</cref>,
under <er>Foul</er>, <pos>a.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In various games or sports, an act done contrary to
the rules; a foul stroke, hit, play, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foulard</ent>⟦br⟧
